metadata.name: Copenhagen Interpretation #108
metadata.description:
The Copenhagen Interpretation of quantum physics suggests that objects don't have physical properties until being observed.

In this generative piece by itsgalo and Spøgelsesmaskinen, a set of objects are being held in "superposition" and finally positioned when observed and minted.

Use mouse/touch to zoom, pan, and rotate. Press 's' to grab a screenshot. Best viewed in Firefox.

metadata.name: Euphonic #631
metadata.description:
Euphonic is an exploration of the emergent visual properties that arise from placing layers of simple lines atop one another.

In general this effect is called the Moiré effect. This effect really feels best in the tactile - when you have a printed page and an acetate sheet. This piece attempts to recreate that tactile joy.

This is built in WebGL 2 and so doesn't work in Safari 14 and below. All latest browsers will work as expected.

Licensing: BY-NC-ND see license.md for details.

metadata.name: Kunza #140
metadata.description:
In 1949, the last known native speaker of Kunza died in the Atacama desert of Chile, leaving behind only fragments of a language that stretched back to when the Incans ruled the region. The textures, patterns, and colors in this project are not intended to be historically accurate: they tell a story. They are my attempt to reach into the past and imagine a vibrant history that is increasingly inaccessible.

Features include weave design, symbol layout, symbol style, and color palette.

After the image has fully rendered, pressing ‘w’, ‘r’, or ‘c’ will toggle different elements of the image, and pressing ‘s’ will download a PNG file.

p5.js

metadata.name: Syzers #109
metadata.description:
Syzers is a generative synthesizer project with sounds altered by Tone JS.

···· On Tuesday, May 17, unsold editions will be burned ····

Visually it consists of 16 layers, in which more than 350 elements are combined randomly, generating synthesizers with unique environments and landscapes.
As for the sound, 40 tracks were recorded with analog synthesizers that were then assigned to each of the modules. These, combined in groups of 4, provide thousands of possible combinations. 
In addition, these sounds will be further modified by code effects that will randomly vary their properties.

Click to listen to the sounds

Many thanks to @Jpupper and @Fipiaggio for help with programming the sound part and @Purespider for the template. 
"FXHASH PFP Token Generator" https://github.com/PureSpider/fxhash-pfp

for best resolution "open live" then use the "download image" button on the lower right corner ;)

metadata.name: Tree Rings #162
metadata.description:
Experimenting with organic movement. Each ring is meant to show the differing growth patterns the tree may have from year to year and what sort of nutrients it's received.

Each Tree Ring has 1 - 9 rings, with 200 - 1000 radians, each ring and background selected from a library of 64 colors.

objkt.name: The Smoothest Cube Over The Number Three #17

metadata.name: The Smoothest Cube Over The Number Three #17
metadata.description:
An infinite experiential soundtrack composed of three notes and three hues. The smoothest cube oscillates between long notes and staccato noise to render a true glitch piece.

The tone and light palette uses a loose adaptation of the Scriabin note to color correspondence. His synesthesia allowed him to perceive color as sounds and he developed a correspondence between pitch and hue with a notable bias for blues and reds.

[click - touch]  Start animation and awesome sounds
[space]          Pause animation as the last note sinks in
[s]              Save PNG file

Artwork by @0xphiiil
